^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|A few things to discuss. First of all, Ruth needs to show that she has a pretty good hand. If an opp overcalls 1NT and you have a good 9 or more, you should double.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It turns out Liza will bid 2@D which is to play (I will discuss an alternative over a penalty double) and that doesn't do that badly. But you need to show values after a 1NT overcall. In fact, if Ruth bids anything but double over 1NT, that is weak and to play.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now if it goes 1 something-1N-dbl-? lets discuss what the responder to the 1N bidder can do. The double shows an invitational hand or better, no upper limit. Absent any other agreement, all systems are off. |
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Suits at the 2 level are to play (e.g 2C is not Stayman, it is clubs). This is only over a double. If Ruth had passed, then systems are on. but when Ruth doubles systems are off. So on this hand, if it goes 1H-1N-dbl, Liza should bid 2@D to play.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The only other conventional bid would be for Liza to redouble. That would be what is known as an "SOS redouble." Once it goes 1H-1N-dbl, responder to the 1N bidder cannot have very many points. |
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The opener has at least 12, the NT bidder has at least 15, the double has at least 9, that leaves at most 4 HCP, usually less for Liza. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So redouble over the double simply says "partner I have no long suit" and "let's try and find a fit." The NT bidder would bid their lowest 4 card suit which would normally be passed by the redoubler.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is another system over the double that I prefer, but you must agree. That system is known as "DONT Runouts." It is basically very similar in concept to DONT. If it goes 1x-1N-dbl, then the responder to 1N usually does one of 2 things if playing DONT runouts. They redouble with a single suited hand (5+ card suit in this case) which is what Liza would have done had Ruth doubled and we were playing DONT runouts. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That would force me to bid 2@C and allow Liza to show her suit. On this hand playing DONT runouts the auction would have gone 1H-1N-dbl-redbl-pass (assume that)-2@C-P-2@D. If Liza did not have a long single suit, she is almost always 4-4 or perhaps 5-4. In that case she would bid her lowest suit. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For example, playing DONT runouts, if it went 1H-1N-dbl-2D, Liza would be showing diamonds and either hearts and spades. I would pass with 3-card support for diamonds, otherwise I would bid 2@H which Liza would pass if she had hearts, or she would bid 2@S if she had spades. Unlike regular DONT, a DONT Runout can be made with as little as 4-4 in 2 suits because they are guaranteed to have at least one 7-card fit at worst.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So you typically would do a DONT Runout with 4-4 or perhaps 5-4 with a weak 5-card suit. On a lucky day, responder might even be 5/5.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I just thought I would mention DONT Runouts as they are interesting but I don't think you necessarily need to play them, because you rarely get doubled in 1N.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I usually play a weak NT with most of my regular partners. In that case, DONT runouts are very effective because they allow us to easily escape from 1N doubled when we need to.|
