^-|CP||fp||at|
After an opening lead, usually in NT contract and if it is 4th best, Rule of 11 is a simple calculation indicating how many cards higher than the card lead, are there in the hands of Dummy, Declarer and opener's partner combined.

For example in a NT contract West leads let us say spot 7, dummy comes down and both declarer and the opener's partner (East) can make the following simple Rule of 11 calculation.

This calculation can be used by both declarer and the opening leader's partner. For declarer, he can calculate how many cards higher than the card led are held by his right hand opponent. For example, if the opening lead is the 7 and there are 3 cards higher than the 7 between dummy and declarer's hand, his right hand opponent holds exactly 1 card higher than the 7. Similarly, opening leader's partner can calculate how many cards higher than the card led are held by declarer.

You cannot use rule of 11 if the opener is leading a card in partner's suit bid or it is an honor including the ten. This information greatly can help the declarer and the defender—although admittedly most non-expert defenders do very little counting.

The explanation why such calculation works is outside the scope of this short synopsis. However, you can refer to this |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.jazclass.aust.com/bridge/rule_11/rule11.htm^*N|CP||AT| link for a nice and simple explanation. However, in the next few panels there would be ample material to make its application understood.|
